# SFTP Server Authorized Keys
# Format: <key-type> <key-data> <username>
#
# This file contains SSH public keys for users who are authorized to access the SFTP server.
# Each line represents one user with three space-separated fields:
#   1. Key type (e.g., ssh-rsa)
#   2. Key data (base64-encoded public key)
#   3. Username (plain username, NOT user@host format)
#
# IMPORTANT: Currently only RSA keys are supported due to Apache SSHD 2.12.0 limitations.
# Ed25519 keys will fail with "No decoder available" error.
#
# Supported key types: ssh-rsa
#
# Generate SSH key pair:
#   ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 2048 -f ~/.ssh/sftp_client_key -N ""
#
# Format the key for authorized_keys:
#   awk '{print $1" "$2" your-username"}' ~/.ssh/sftp_client_key.pub > keys/authorized_keys
#
# To use this file:
#   1. Copy this file to keys/authorized_keys:
#      cp keys/authorized_keys.example keys/authorized_keys
#   2. Replace the example entries below with your actual SSH public keys
#   3. Ensure the format is: <key-type> <key-data> <username> (three fields)
#   4. Username should be plain text (e.g., "alice" not "alice@hostname")
#   5. Set proper permissions: chmod 600 keys/authorized_keys
#   6. Restart the SFTP server
#
# Example entries (replace with your actual RSA keys):

# ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc2EAAAADAQABAAABAQCexamplekeydata1234567890 policyholder-consumer
# ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc2EAAAADAQABAAABAQDdifferentkeydata0987654321 data-analyst
# ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1yc2EAAAADAQABAAABAQCanotherkeyhere999888777666 backup-service
